ional Church Order,” won, and was ordained pastor of the new Second Church — which celebrated its 350th anniversary in 2020."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"His bride’s father sailed the phantom ship","body":"His second wife Phebe was the daughter of Thomas Gregson of New Haven, lost at sea in 1646 aboard the famous “phantom ship.” Phebe outlived Whiting by forty-one years, remarrying Rev. John Russell of Hadley."}],"slug":"john-whiting-1635"},"X03368":{"id":"X03368","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":true,"generation_from_thomas":null},"bio":{"display_name":"Sibyl Collins Whiting","first_name":"Sibyl","last_name":"Whiting","maiden_name":"Collins","married_names":["Whiting"],"bio_blurb":"First wife of Rev. John Whiting","gender":"female"},"birth":{"year":1633,"month":4,"day":3,"city":"Framlingham","state":"Suffolk","country":"England","date_precision":"exact","notes":"Some sources give Nov 1636/1637"},"death":{"year":1672,"month":6,"day":4,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","date_precision":"exact"},"parents":{"father_id":null,"mother_id":null,"father_research_notes":"Edward Collins","mother_research_notes":"Martha Collins"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00083","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1654,"location_city":"Cambridge","location_state":"Massachusetts","location_country":"United States","children_ids":["X03371"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"A minister's first wife, gone too soon","body":"Sibyl Collins married Rev. John Whiting around 1654 and bore his earliest children before her death in 1672. Daughter of Edward Collins and sister of Rev. John Collins, she connected two ministerial families of early New England.","category":"religion","number":1},{"header":"Her sons commanded armies and pulpits","body":"Two of Sibyl's sons rose to prominence: Col. William Whiting led Connecticut troops against French and Indian forces and later served as High Sherif